<subSubSection id="33CB651CFFBAFFFA5BE9F9BDE246F9CA" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="7B6E3697FFBAFFFA5BE9F9BDE246F9CA" blockId="27.[192,1441,291,1915]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5BE9F9BDE6C4F9ED" bold="true" box="[240,392,1539,1563]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name means “like a mirror” and refers to the shining patches on the dorsal hindwing and ventral forewing. The former is more extensive than it is on most species in the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="33CB651CFFBAFFFA5BE9F9FDE200F9AD" box="[240,1356,1603,1627]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7B6E3697FFBAFFFA5BE9F9FDE200F9AD" blockId="27.[192,1441,291,1915]" box="[240,1356,1603,1627]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5BE9F9FDE53BF9AD" bold="true" box="[240,631,1603,1627]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Distribution and phenology.</emphasis>
The species is known only from the 
<typeStatus id="A46A8835FFBAFFFA5F35F9FDE3DAF9AD" box="[1068,1174,1603,1627]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">holotype</typeStatus>
taken in June.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="33CB651CFFBAFFFD5BE9F9DDE4D6FE8D" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="7B6E3697FFBAFFFD5BE9F9DDE304FECD" blockId="27.[192,1441,291,1915]" lastBlockId="28.[192,1440,195,379]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="27" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5BE9F9DDE518F98D" bold="true" box="[240,596,1635,1659]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Diagnosis and discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBAFFFA5942F9DDE4DFF98D" authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[603,915,1635,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="specularis">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5942F9DDE4DFF98D" box="[603,915,1635,1659]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Porphyrogenes specularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears most similar to the male assigned by 
<bibRefCitation id="1F404B66FFBAFFFA5BFAF93AE6CEF96D" author="Evans, W. H." box="[227,386,1667,1691]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" refId="ref35584" refString="Evans, W. H. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae in the British Museum. Part II (groups B, C, D), Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History); London. 178 p." type="book" year="1952">Evans (1952)</bibRefCitation>
to 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBAFFFA5ABDF93AE579F96D" baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[420,565,1667,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sororcula">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5ABDF93AE579F96D" box="[420,565,1667,1691]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">P. sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see also above under that species). 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBAFFFA58FEF93DE25EF96D" baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[999,1298,1667,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sororcula">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA58FEF93DE25EF96D" box="[999,1298,1667,1691]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Porphyrogenes sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was named from a single female from 
<collectingCountry id="03C67607FFBAFFFA5AE3F91DE5FEF94D" box="[506,690,1699,1723]" name="French Guiana" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="1F404B66FFBAFFFA59D9F91DE4BFF94D" author="Mabille, P. &amp; E. Boullet" box="[704,1011,1699,1723]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" pagination="1 - 159" refId="ref36122" refString="Mabille, P., and E. Boullet. 1912. Essai de revision de la famille des hesperides. Annales des Sciences Naturelles (Zoologie) 16: 1 - 159." type="journal article" year="1912">Mabille and Boullet 1912</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<bibRefCitation id="1F404B66FFBAFFFA5F2CF91AE398F94D" author="Evans, W. H." box="[1077,1236,1699,1723]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" refId="ref35584" refString="Evans, W. H. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae in the British Museum. Part II (groups B, C, D), Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History); London. 178 p." type="book" year="1952">Evans (1952)</bibRefCitation>
was unsure if he properly associated a male, also from 
<collectingCountry id="03C67607FFBAFFFA5991F97DE408F92D" box="[648,836,1731,1755]" name="French Guiana" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
, at the BM(NH). 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBAFFFA5F0AF97DE206F92D" authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[1043,1354,1731,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="specularis">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5F0AF97DE206F92D" box="[1043,1354,1731,1755]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">Porphyrogenes specularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
apparently differs from that male in several respects. The hindwing has the central portion of the anal margin convex (this reported as “nearly straight” for 
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA59C6F8BAE5B4F8ED" box="[735,760,1796,1819]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">P.</emphasis>
“ 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBAFFFA5811F8BDE437F8ED" baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[776,891,1795,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sororcula">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5811F8BDE437F8ED" box="[776,891,1795,1819]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” by 
<bibRefCitation id="1F404B66FFBAFFFA58B4F8BAE370F8ED" author="Evans, W. H." box="[941,1084,1795,1819]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" refId="ref35584" refString="Evans, W. H. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae in the British Museum. Part II (groups B, C, D), Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History); London. 178 p." type="book" year="1952">Evans 1952</bibRefCitation>
) and no mention was made of a prominent speculum anteriad on the dorsal hindwing. Additionally, 
<bibRefCitation id="1F404B66FFBAFFFA5F07F89AE3F3F8CD" author="Evans, W. H." box="[1054,1215,1827,1851]" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" refId="ref35584" refString="Evans, W. H. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae in the British Museum. Part II (groups B, C, D), Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History); London. 178 p." type="book" year="1952">Evans (1952)</bibRefCitation>
reported the tufts (erroneously as on the forewing) as being brown on 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBAFFFA5828F8FAE488F8AD" baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[817,964,1859,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sororcula">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5828F8FAE488F8AD" box="[817,964,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">P. sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the anterior is brown on 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBAFFFA5FE5F8FAE2D4F8AD" authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[1276,1432,1859,1883]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="specularis">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBAFFFA5FE5F8FAE2D4F8AD" box="[1276,1432,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="26">P. specularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the posterior is a much paler tan in color. The genitalia of the taxon from Rondônia also show several differences from those illustrated for 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBDFFFD5963FF7AE445FF2D" baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[634,777,195,219]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sororcula">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBDFFFD5963FF7AE445FF2D" box="[634,777,195,219]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">P. sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="1F404B66FFBDFFFD5828FF7AE485FF2D" author="Evans, W. H." box="[817,969,195,219]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" refId="ref35584" refString="Evans, W. H. 1952. A catalogue of the American Hesperiidae in the British Museum. Part II (groups B, C, D), Pyrginae. Section I. British Museum (Natural History); London. 178 p." type="book" year="1952">Evans (1952</bibRefCitation>
; note again that his genitalic figures for 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBDFFFD5BD9FF5DE639FF0D" box="[192,373,227,251]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBDFFFD5BD9FF5DE639FF0D" box="[192,373,227,251]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">Porphyrogenes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are uniformly poor): the tegumen is shorter, the uncus is much narrower with its arms more closely spaced, and the valva is longer with the harpe more elongate and costa/ampulla broader. We believe that the male of 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBDFFFD5AFBFE9AE538FECD" baseAuthorityName="Mabille and Boullet" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[482,628,291,315]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sororcula">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBDFFFD5AFBFE9AE538FECD" box="[482,628,291,315]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">P. sororcula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBDFFFD598DFE9DE4F9FECD" authorityName="Skinner" authorityYear="1920" box="[660,949,291,315]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Bungalotis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="immaculata">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBDFFFD598DFE9DE4F9FECD" box="[660,949,291,315]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">Bungalotis immaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7B6E3697FFBDFFFD5BE9FEFDE4D6FE8D" blockId="28.[192,1440,195,379]" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName id="BCD14D14FFBDFFFD5BE9FEFDE565FEAD" authorityName="Austin and Mielke" authorityYear="2008" box="[240,553,323,347]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Porphyrogenes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="specularis">
<emphasis id="49A5EA85FFBDFFFD5BE9FEFDE565FEAD" box="[240,553,323,347]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="27">Porphyrogenes specularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is readily recognized by the extensive speculum on the dorsal hindwing with the conspicuous dark brown tuft from its proximal end.
</paragraph>
